{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DdqsNTFUAjR9g5LxfD6fw1","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Specification: 100 Close Call\n     2→\n     3→## Meta\n     4→\n     5→| Field | Value |\n     6→|-------|-------|\n     7→| Status | Done |\n     8→| Ideation | Active |\n     9→| Priority | P2 |\n    10→| Phase | V1.5 |\n    11→| NR_OF_TRIES | 46 |\n    12→\n    13→---\n    14→\n    15→## Overview\n    16→\n    17→Close Call is a pari-mutuel prediction game where players bet on whether a one-minute BTC candle will close green (bullish) or red (bearish). Winners share the losing side's pool proportionally to their wager. Rounds are synchronized to minute boundaries with continuous play. Oracle-resolved via Pyth Network — no commit-reveal, no server secret. This uses flexible betting (any amount, no tiers).\n    18→\n    19→## User Stories\n    20→\n    21→- As a player, I want to bet on the next candle's direction so that I can profit from my market intuition.\n    22→- As a player, I want to see the current candle forming live so that I can make an informed bet.\n    23→- As a player, I want to see pool sizes and implied odds so that I understand my potential payout.\n    24→- As a player, I want automatic payouts when I win, without needing to claim.\n    25→- As a player, I want a full refund if a round is invalid (one-sided, equal price) so I never lose funds unfairly.\n    26→\n    27→---\n    28→\n    29→## Scope Alignment\n    30→\n    31→- **`docs/SCOPE.md` references**: Post-V1 (V1.5 candidate)\n    32→- **Scope status**: Active design\n    33→- **Phase boundary**: V1.5\n    34→\n    35→## Required Context Files\n    36→\n    37→- `sources/rng-utopia/docs/CLOSE_CALL.md` (game concept source)\n    38→- `sources/rng-utopia/docs/PLATFORM.md` (flexible betting, platform fee)\n    39→\n    40→## Contract Files\n    41→\n    42→- `solana/programs/closecall/src/state.rs` (on-chain account definitions)\n    43→- `solana/programs/closecall/src/instructions/` (instruction handlers)\n    44→\n    45→---\n    46→\n    47→## Functional Requirements\n    48→\n    49→### FR-1: Round Structure\n    50→\n    51→Rounds follow a fixed 60-second cycle synchronized to minute boundaries. Each round has a 30-second betting window followed by a 30-second lock period. The backend creates rounds at minute boundaries.\n    52→\n    53→**Timing:**\n    54→- **Betting window**: 30 seconds (configurable on-chain via CloseCallConfig)\n    55→- **Lock period**: 30 seconds (remaining time until candle close)\n    56→- **Total cycle**: 60 seconds aligned to clock minutes\n    57→\n    58→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    59→- [ ] Rounds aligned to minute boundaries (e.g., 12:00:00, 12:01:00)\n    60→- [ ] Betting window is 30 seconds from round start (configurable)\n    61→- [ ] Bets rejected after betting window closes\n    62→- [ ] Round resolves at minute boundary when candle closes\n    63→- [ ] Backend creates new round automatically at each minute boundary\n    64→- [ ] Clear label showing which candle the bet applies to\n    65→\n    66→### FR-2: Bet Placement\n    67→\n    68→Players choose GREEN (bull) or RED (bear) with any amount within platform limits. One bet per player per round. Maximum 32 entries per side (64 total) to fit auto-payout in a single transaction.\n    69→\n    70→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    71→- [ ] Two prediction options: GREEN (close > open) and RED (close < open)\n    72→- [ ] Flexible bet amount with 1/2, x2, MAX controls\n    73→- [ ] Minimum bet: 0.001 SOL (platform minimum)\n    74→- [ ] Maximum bet: 100 SOL (platform maximum)\n    75→- [ ] One bet per player per round (enforced on-chain)\n    76→- [ ] Bet locked immediately, cannot change or cancel\n    77→- [ ] Maximum 32 entries per side (64 total per round)\n    78→- [ ] UI shows \"needs bets on both sides to activate\" when pool is one-sided\n    79→\n    80→### FR-3: Outcome Determination\n    81→\n    82→Outcome based on strict comparison of candle close vs open price from Pyth Network oracle. No DOJI threshold — exact equality triggers refund.\n    83→\n    84→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    85→- [ ] GREEN wins if close price > open price (strict)\n    86→- [ ] RED wins if close price < open price (strict)\n    87→- [ ] Equal price (close == open): full refund, no fee\n    88→- [ ] Price data sourced from Pyth Network on-chain price account\n    89→- [ ] Open price stored in round PDA at creation time\n    90→- [ ] Close price read from Pyth account at settlement time\n    91→- [ ] On-chain program verifies Pyth price account directly\n    92→- [ ] Supported asset at launch: BTC/USD\n    93→\n    94→### FR-4: Payout and Fee\n    95→\n    96→Fee is 3% of total pool, collected at settlement of decisive rounds only. Auto-payout to all winners proportionally via remaining accounts.\n    97→\n    98→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    99→- [ ] Fee = 3% of total pool (200 bps revenue + 70 bps rakeback + 30 bps chest)\n   100→- [ ] Net pool = total pool × 0.97\n   101→- [ ] Winner payout = (player_bet / winning_pool) × net_pool\n   102→- [ ] Fee collected only on decisive rounds (both sides have bets, close ≠ open)\n   103→- [ ] Auto-payout to all winners in settlement transaction (no claim step)\n   104→- [ ] Payout via remaining accounts pattern (same as lord-of-rngs)\n   105→\n   106→### FR-5: Invalid Round Handling\n   107→\n   108→Invalid rounds result in full refund with no fee. No carryover mechanics.\n   109→\n   110→| Condition | Treatment | Fee |\n   111→|-----------|-----------|-----|\n   112→| close > open (both sides have bets) | Auto-payout to GREEN bettors | 3% of total pool |\n   113→| close < open (both sides have bets) | Auto-payout to RED bettors | 3% of total pool |\n   114→| close == open | Refund all bets | None |\n   115→| One-sided pool (all bets on same side) | Refund all bets | None |\n   116→| Single player only | Refund all bets | None |\n   117→| No bets placed | Close round PDA, no action | None |\n   118→\n   119→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   120→- [ ] Equal price → full refund to all players, no fee deducted\n   121→- [ ] One-sided pool → full refund to all players, no fee deducted\n   122→- [ ] Single player → full refund, no fee deducted\n   123→- [ ] No bets → round closed cleanly, no transfers\n   124→- [ ] Refunds return exact deposit amounts (no rounding loss)\n   125→\n   126→### FR-6: Settlement\n   127→\n   128→Oracle-resolved settlement. No commit-reveal — no server secret. Backend reads Pyth close price and submits settle transaction. On-chain program verifies close price from Pyth account. Timeout refund available if backend fails to settle.\n   129→\n   130→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   131→- [ ] Settlement triggered by backend after candle close\n   132→- [ ] Round state machine: BETTING → LOCKED → SETTLED or REFUNDED\n   133→- [ ] On-chain program reads Pyth price account at settlement\n   134→- [ ] Double-settle prevention via phase state machine\n   135→- [ ] Settlement transaction is atomic (all payouts or all refunds in one tx)\n   136→- [ ] Timeout refund available permissionlessly after resolve deadline\n   137→- [ ] Server pays rent on round creation, gets rent back on close\n   138→- [ ] Pyth prices verifiable by anyone (oracle transparency)\n   139→\n   140→### FR-7: Game UI\n   141→\n   142→Live candlestick chart with betting panel, pool visualization, and countdown timer.\n   143→\n   144→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   145→- [ ] Large candlestick chart showing recent BTC/USD history\n   146→- [ ] Current candle highlighted with live price indicator\n   147→- [ ] Betting panel with amount input and GREEN/RED buttons\n   148→- [ ] Pool sizes for GREEN and RED shown with distribution percentage\n   149→- [ ] Active stake display if player has a pending bet\n   150→- [ ] Countdown timer showing betting window remaining\n   151→- [ ] Resolution animation: GREEN/RED result display\n   152→- [ ] Clear indication of round outcome and player result\n   153→\n   154→---\n   155→\n   156→## On-Chain Architecture\n   157→\n   158→### Account PDAs\n   159→\n   160→| Account | Seeds | Purpose |\n   161→|---------|-------|---------|\n   162→| `CloseCallConfig` | `[\"closecall_config\"]` | Treasury, timing params, pause flag, max entries per side, Pyth feed address |\n   163→| `CloseCallRound` | `[\"cc_round\", round_id]` | Per-round: entries (green/red), pool totals, open/close prices, outcome, phase |\n   164→\n   165→Two PDA types. Same minimal pattern as coinflip.\n   166→\n   167→### Instructions\n   168→\n   169→| Instruction | Who calls | What it does |\n   170→|-------------|-----------|-------------|\n   171→| `initialize_config` | Authority | One-time config setup (treasury, timing, Pyth feed) |\n   172→| `create_round` | Server | Creates round PDA, stores Pyth open price, pays rent |\n   173→| `place_bet` | Player | Deposits SOL into round PDA, picks GREEN or RED |\n   174→| `settle_round` | Server | Reads Pyth close price on-chain, determines outcome: pay winners or refund all |\n   175→| `timeout_refund` | Anyone | Permissionless after resolve_deadline — refunds all players |\n   176→| `force_close` | Authority | Emergency admin close — refunds all |\n   177→\n   178→6 instructions.\n   179→\n   180→### Fee Model\n   181→\n   182→Fee = 3% of total pool, collected at settlement of decisive rounds.\n   183→- Decisive round: `fee = 3% × total_pool`. Winners share `net_pool = total_pool - fee`.\n   184→- Invalid round: NO fee. Full refund to all players.\n   185→- Example: Green pool 7 SOL + Red pool 3 SOL = 10 SOL total. Green wins. Fee = 0.30 SOL. Green bettors share 9.70 SOL proportionally.\n   186→\n   187→### Shared Crate Reuse\n   188→\n   189→From `solana/shared/src/`:\n   190→- `escrow.rs` — `transfer_lamports_from_pda`, `transfer_lamports_to_pda`, `close_pda`\n   191→- `fees.rs` — `calculate_net_payout`, `split_fee`\n   192→- `wager.rs` — `validate_wager`\n   193→- `timeout.rs` — `is_expired`\n   194→- `pause.rs` — `check_not_paused`\n   195→\n   196→Program reads Pyth push oracle price accounts directly (no SDK dependency — manual parser in `pyth.rs`).\n   197→\n   198→---\n   199→\n   200→## Success Criteria\n   201→\n   202→- A player can bet on candle direction, watch it resolve, and receive proportional auto-payout\n   203→- Pari-mutuel payouts are mathematically correct for all pool distributions\n   204→- Invalid rounds (equal price, one-sided, single player) refund fully with no fee\n   205→- Settlement is idempotent and atomic\n   206→- Price data is from a verifiable oracle source (Pyth Network)\n   207→- Timeout refund protects players if backend fails\n   208→\n   209→---\n   210→\n   211→## Dependencies\n   212→\n   213→- Pyth Network price feed integration (on-chain `PriceUpdateV2` account)\n   214→- Platform flexible betting system\n   215→- On-chain settlement infrastructure (shared crate)\n   216→- Real-time WebSocket for live price display (existing `packages/price-feeds`)\n   217→\n   218→## Assumptions\n   219→\n   220→- BTC/USD is the only asset at launch\n   221→- Pyth Network provides sufficiently low-latency price data for 1-minute candles\n   222→- 64 max entries per round fits within single-transaction compute budget for auto-payout\n   223→- Backend clock worker reliably creates and settles rounds at minute boundaries\n   224→\n   225→---\n   226→\n   227→## Validation Plan\n   228→\n   229→| # | Acceptance Criterion | Validation Method | Evidence Required |\n   230→|---|---------------------|-------------------|-------------------|\n   231→| 1 | Round aligned to minute boundaries | Observe round transitions at :00 marks | Timestamps in logs |\n   232→| 2 | Pari-mutuel payout correct | Multi-player round, verify proportional payouts | Calculation proof |\n   233→| 3 | Equal price triggers full refund | Force equal-price condition | All bets returned, no fee |\n   234→| 4 | One-sided pool triggers refund | All bets on one side | All bets returned, no fee |\n   235→| 5 | Settlement idempotent | Attempt double-settle | Error response proof |\n   236→| 6 | Price from Pyth verified | Compare on-chain price vs Pyth feed | Price comparison |\n   237→| 7 | Timeout refund works | Let resolve deadline expire | Permissionless refund succeeds |\n   238→| 8 | Auto-payout delivered | Win a round | Lamports arrive without claim tx |\n   239→\n   240→---\n   241→\n   242→## Completion Signal\n   243→\n   244→### Implementation Checklist\n   245→\n   246→Items are ordered by dependency. Each unchecked item = one autonomous iteration.\n   247→\n   248→#### On-chain program — DONE (iteration 0)\n   249→- [x] [on-chain] CloseCallConfig + CloseCallRound PDAs, all 6 instructions, fee calc, invalid round handling, manual Pyth PriceUpdateV2 parser (`pyth.rs`)\n   250→- [x] [test] Bankrun tests: 20 tests covering all instructions + edge cases (equal price, one-sided, single player, max entries, timeout)\n   251→\n   252→#### Phase 1: Pyth + Anchor Client\n   253→- [x] [on-chain] Verify `pyth.rs` parser works with Pyth push oracle price accounts on devnet (BTC/USD feed). If the devnet Pyth accounts use a different format than PriceUpdateV2, adapt the parser. Find the correct Pyth BTC/USD price account address for devnet. Update bankrun tests with correct mock format if changed. Run `anchor build` + bankrun tests to confirm. (done: iteration 1)\n   254→- [x] [engine] Copy `solana/target/idl/closecall.json` and `solana/target/types/closecall.ts` into `packages/anchor-client/src/`. Add `closecall` to the barrel export in `packages/anchor-client/src/index.ts` following the exact pattern used for coinflip and lordofrngs (IDL JSON import + type re-export). Add `CLOSECALL_PROGRAM_ID` constant to `packages/config/`. Run `pnpm lint` in the anchor-client package to confirm no errors. (done: iteration 2)\n   255→\n   256→#### Phase 2: Backend\n   257→- [x] [backend] In `services/backend/src/worker/account-decoder.ts`, add `DecodedCloseCallRound` and `DecodedCloseCallConfig` interfaces + decoder functions using `BorshAccountsCoder` from the closecall IDL. Follow the exact pattern of the existing coinflip/lordofrngs decoders (bnToBigInt conversion, phase enum mapping). Export from module. Run `pnpm lint` to confirm. (done: iteration 3)\n   258→- [x] [backend] In `services/backend/src/worker/settle-tx.ts`, add closecall settlement functions: `buildCreateRoundTx(roundId, pythPriceAccount)`, `buildSettleRoundTx(roundId, pythPriceAccount, winnerAccounts)`, `buildTimeoutRefundTx(roundId, playerAccounts)`. The backend reads the Pyth push oracle price account via `connection.getAccountInfo()` — no Hermes fetch needed. Follow the existing coinflip/lordofrngs settle pattern. Run `pnpm lint` to confirm. (done: iteration 4)\n   259→- [x] [backend] Create `services/backend/src/worker/closecall-clock.ts` — a `CloseCallClockWorker` that runs on minute-boundary intervals. Each tick: (1) read Pyth BTC/USD push oracle price from Solana via RPC, (2) settle the previous round if it exists and candle has closed (call `buildSettleRoundTx`), (3) create a new round (call `buildCreateRoundTx` with open price from Pyth account). Use the existing `retry.ts` pattern for tx submission. Handle edge cases: no previous round, settlement failure (log + continue). Export worker class. (done: iteration 5)\n   260→- [x] [backend] Extend DB: add `game = \"closecall\"` support to the `rounds` table (or create a new `closecall_rounds` table if schema differs significantly). Store: round_id, open_price, close_price, outcome, green_pool, red_pool, fee, created_at, settled_at, tx_signature. Add API routes: `GET /closecall/current-round` (returns active round + pool state), `GET /closecall/history` (last 20 settled rounds). Extend `GET /fairness/rounds/by-id/:roundId` to support closecall rounds. Follow the existing route creation pattern in `services/backend/src/routes/`. (done: iteration 6)\n   261→- [x] [backend] Wire the `CloseCallClockWorker` into `services/backend/src/index.ts`: import, instantiate with config (Pyth BTC/USD account address, server keypair, connection, DB), start on backend boot. Add `PYTH_BTC_USD_ACCOUNT` env var to `.env` and config loading. Run `pnpm lint` across backend to confirm. Verify the backend starts without errors (even if clock worker won't find rounds on devnet yet). (done: iteration 7)\n   262→\n   263→#### Phase 3: Devnet Deploy\n   264→- [x] [deploy] Deploy closecall program to devnet: `anchor deploy --provider.cluster devnet -p closecall`. Run `initialize_config` on devnet (treasury from `.env.devnet`, Pyth BTC/USD feed ID for devnet, 30s betting window, 32 max entries per side). Add `VITE_CLOSECALL_PROGRAM_ID=8TXq2XyHsk5AAMkoyk5QtG25xyyY7rTMHXrJRHRwjUpA` to `.env.devnet`. Verify by calling `create_round` + `place_bet` + `settle_round` manually against real Pyth prices. (done: iteration 8)\n   265→\n   266→#### Phase 4: Frontend Integration (existing mock scaffolding → real)\n   267→\n   268→Note: FE scaffolding already exists at `apps/platform/src/features/close-call/` with mock simulation. Route, sidebar nav entry, and component structure are already in place. These iterations swap mocks for real backend/on-chain integration.\n   269→\n   270→- [x] [frontend] Update `features/close-call/types.ts`: remove DOJI threshold, carryover, commit-reveal fields (`seedHash`, `serverSeed`, `blockHash`, `carryoverAmount`). Remove `claimPayout` from context actions (auto-payout). Fix constants: `BETTING_WINDOW_MS = 30000` (was 10000), `MIN_BET_AMOUNT` to 0.001 SOL, `MAX_BET_AMOUNT` to 100 SOL. Align `RoundPhase` with on-chain `CloseCallPhase` (Open/Settled/Refunded). Align `CandleOutcome` — remove \"doji\", add \"refund\". Update `PoolState` to match on-chain `green_pool`/`red_pool` fields. Run `pnpm lint` to confirm no type errors cascade. (done: iteration 30)\n   271→- [x] [frontend] Rewrite `features/close-call/context/CloseCallContext.tsx`: replace `mock-simulation.ts` imports with real backend API calls (`GET /closecall/current-round` for active round + pools, `GET /closecall/history` for recent rounds). Poll current round every 2s (or use existing event subscription pattern from coinflip). Read Pyth BTC/USD price for chart via existing `packages/price-feeds` `usePriceSubscription(\"BTC\")`. Remove `claimPayout()`, remove carryover/jackpot state. Keep `placeBet()` as a stub that calls the wallet tx (wired in next iteration). Run `pnpm lint` + verify page loads without crash. (done: iteration 39)\n   272→- [x] [frontend] Wire wallet integration for `place_bet`: in `CloseCallContext.tsx`, implement `placeBet()` to build and send a `place_bet` transaction using the closecall IDL from `packages/anchor-client`. Follow the exact pattern used in coinflip for tx building + signing via `useWallet()`. Handle errors: insufficient balance → toast, betting closed race → toast + refresh round, tx failure → toast with retry. On successful bet, optimistically update `userBet` in context, then confirm via next poll. Remove `mock-simulation.ts` and `payout-calculator.ts` if fully replaced. Run `pnpm lint`. (done: iteration 40)\n   273→- [x] [frontend] Add `/close-call/:roundId` deep-link page: create `pages/CloseCallRoundPage.tsx` (follow pattern of `CoinflipRoundPage`). Fetch round data from `GET /fairness/rounds/by-id/:roundId`. Display: open price, close price, outcome (Green/Red/Refund), green pool, red pool, total pool, fee collected, entries list, settlement tx signature. Add route to `App.tsx`. Link from round history list. Run `pnpm lint`. (done: iteration 41)\n   274→\n   275→#### Phase 5: Testing\n   276→- [x] [test] Update visual baselines for close-call pages. Run `pnpm test:visual` to identify failures, then `pnpm test:visual:update` to regenerate. **Before committing**: read old baseline and new screenshot for each changed page (use Read tool on PNG files). Evaluate: **PASS** (changes clearly match spec intent) → commit. **REVIEW** (unexpected areas changed) → save diff images, describe in history.md, output blocker. **FAIL** (broken layout) → fix code, don't update baselines. (done: iteration 42)\n   277→- [x] [test] ~~Add local deterministic E2E coverage~~ N/A: Close Call requires Pyth oracle price accounts (PriceUpdateV2 owned by Pyth Solana Receiver) on localnet — no Pyth program stack deployed locally. Backend clock worker also needs Pyth to create rounds. Frontend has no mock mode fallback. Devnet E2E (next item) provides integration coverage with real Pyth data. (done: iteration 43)\n   278→- [x] [test] Add visual route/state coverage in `e2e/visual/**`; run `pnpm test:visual` and update baselines only for intentional UI changes (done: iteration 44)\n   279→- [x] [test] If external provider/oracle/VRF integration is in scope, add devnet real-provider E2E coverage in `e2e/devnet/**` with env validation + retry/backoff (or mark N/A with reason) (done: iteration 45)\n   280→\n   281→### Testing Requirements\n   282→\n   283→The agent MUST complete ALL before outputting the completion signal:\n   284→\n   285→#### Code Quality\n   286→- [ ] All existing tests pass\n   287→- [x] New bankrun tests for all 6 instructions (done: iteration 0)\n   288→- [x] New tests for pari-mutuel payout calculations (done: iteration 0)\n   289→- [x] New tests for invalid round conditions (done: iteration 0)\n   290→- [ ] No lint errors\n   291→\n   292→#### Functional Verification\n   293→- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified\n   294→- [ ] Edge cases: equal price, single-sided pool, max entries reached, timeout refund\n   295→- [ ] Settlement idempotency verified\n   296→- [ ] Auto-payout delivers correct amounts\n   297→\n   298→#### Visual Verification\n   299→- [ ] Chart and betting UI correct on desktop\n   300→- [ ] Mobile responsive layout works\n   301→\n   302→#### Console/Network Check\n   303→- [ ] No JS console errors\n   304→- [ ] No failed network requests\n   305→\n   306→### Iteration Instructions\n   307→\n   308→If ANY check fails:\n   309→1. Identify the specific issue\n   310→2. Fix the code\n   311→3. Re-run tests\n   312→4. Re-verify all criteria\n   313→5. Check again\n   314→\n   315→**Only when ALL checks pass, output:** `<promise>DONE</promise>`\n   316→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"efe120e9-7ceb-4e75-b227-230da807bdef","uuid":"47bacfd7-091d-4254-aa15-e7a04e3234e2","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/docs/specs/100-close-call/spec.md","content":"# Specification: 100 Close Call\n\n## Meta\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| Status | Done |\n| Ideation | Active |\n| Priority | P2 |\n| Phase | V1.5 |\n| NR_OF_TRIES | 46 |\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nClose Call is a pari-mutuel prediction game where players bet on whether a one-minute BTC candle will close green (bullish) or red (bearish). Winners share the losing side's pool proportionally to their wager. Rounds are synchronized to minute boundaries with continuous play. Oracle-resolved via Pyth Network — no commit-reveal, no server secret. This uses flexible betting (any amount, no tiers).\n\n## User Stories\n\n- As a player, I want to bet on the next candle's direction so that I can profit from my market intuition.\n- As a player, I want to see the current candle forming live so that I can make an informed bet.\n- As a player, I want to see pool sizes and implied odds so that I understand my potential payout.\n- As a player, I want automatic payouts when I win, without needing to claim.\n- As a player, I want a full refund if a round is invalid (one-sided, equal price) so I never lose funds unfairly.\n\n---\n\n## Scope Alignment\n\n- **`docs/SCOPE.md` references**: Post-V1 (V1.5 candidate)\n- **Scope status**: Active design\n- **Phase boundary**: V1.5\n\n## Required Context Files\n\n- `sources/rng-utopia/docs/CLOSE_CALL.md` (game concept source)\n- `sources/rng-utopia/docs/PLATFORM.md` (flexible betting, platform fee)\n\n## Contract Files\n\n- `solana/programs/closecall/src/state.rs` (on-chain account definitions)\n- `solana/programs/closecall/src/instructions/` (instruction handlers)\n\n---\n\n## Functional Requirements\n\n### FR-1: Round Structure\n\nRounds follow a fixed 60-second cycle synchronized to minute boundaries. Each round has a 30-second betting window followed by a 30-second lock period. The backend creates rounds at minute boundaries.\n\n**Timing:**\n- **Betting window**: 30 seconds (configurable on-chain via CloseCallConfig)\n- **Lock period**: 30 seconds (remaining time until candle close)\n- **Total cycle**: 60 seconds aligned to clock minutes\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Rounds aligned to minute boundaries (e.g., 12:00:00, 12:01:00)\n- [ ] Betting window is 30 seconds from round start (configurable)\n- [ ] Bets rejected after betting window closes\n- [ ] Round resolves at minute boundary when candle closes\n- [ ] Backend creates new round automatically at each minute boundary\n- [ ] Clear label showing which candle the bet applies to\n\n### FR-2: Bet Placement\n\nPlayers choose GREEN (bull) or RED (bear) with any amount within platform limits. One bet per player per round. Maximum 32 entries per side (64 total) to fit auto-payout in a single transaction.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Two prediction options: GREEN (close > open) and RED (close < open)\n- [ ] Flexible bet amount with 1/2, x2, MAX controls\n- [ ] Minimum bet: 0.001 SOL (platform minimum)\n- [ ] Maximum bet: 100 SOL (platform maximum)\n- [ ] One bet per player per round (enforced on-chain)\n- [ ] Bet locked immediately, cannot change or cancel\n- [ ] Maximum 32 entries per side (64 total per round)\n- [ ] UI shows \"needs bets on both sides to activate\" when pool is one-sided\n\n### FR-3: Outcome Determination\n\nOutcome based on strict comparison of candle close vs open price from Pyth Network oracle. No DOJI threshold — exact equality triggers refund.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] GREEN wins if close price > open price (strict)\n- [ ] RED wins if close price < open price (strict)\n- [ ] Equal price (close == open): full refund, no fee\n- [ ] Price data sourced from Pyth Network on-chain price account\n- [ ] Open price stored in round PDA at creation time\n- [ ] Close price read from Pyth account at settlement time\n- [ ] On-chain program verifies Pyth price account directly\n- [ ] Supported asset at launch: BTC/USD\n\n### FR-4: Payout and Fee\n\nFee is 3% of total pool, collected at settlement of decisive rounds only. Auto-payout to all winners proportionally via remaining accounts.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Fee = 3% of total pool (200 bps revenue + 70 bps rakeback + 30 bps chest)\n- [ ] Net pool = total pool × 0.97\n- [ ] Winner payout = (player_bet / winning_pool) × net_pool\n- [ ] Fee collected only on decisive rounds (both sides have bets, close ≠ open)\n- [ ] Auto-payout to all winners in settlement transaction (no claim step)\n- [ ] Payout via remaining accounts pattern (same as lord-of-rngs)\n\n### FR-5: Invalid Round Handling\n\nInvalid rounds result in full refund with no fee. No carryover mechanics.\n\n| Condition | Treatment | Fee |\n|-----------|-----------|-----|\n| close > open (both sides have bets) | Auto-payout to GREEN bettors | 3% of total pool |\n| close < open (both sides have bets) | Auto-payout to RED bettors | 3% of total pool |\n| close == open | Refund all bets | None |\n| One-sided pool (all bets on same side) | Refund all bets | None |\n| Single player only | Refund all bets | None |\n| No bets placed | Close round PDA, no action | None |\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Equal price → full refund to all players, no fee deducted\n- [ ] One-sided pool → full refund to all players, no fee deducted\n- [ ] Single player → full refund, no fee deducted\n- [ ] No bets → round closed cleanly, no transfers\n- [ ] Refunds return exact deposit amounts (no rounding loss)\n\n### FR-6: Settlement\n\nOracle-resolved settlement. No commit-reveal — no server secret. Backend reads Pyth close price and submits settle transaction. On-chain program verifies close price from Pyth account. Timeout refund available if backend fails to settle.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Settlement triggered by backend after candle close\n- [ ] Round state machine: BETTING → LOCKED → SETTLED or REFUNDED\n- [ ] On-chain program reads Pyth price account at settlement\n- [ ] Double-settle prevention via phase state machine\n- [ ] Settlement transaction is atomic (all payouts or all refunds in one tx)\n- [ ] Timeout refund available permissionlessly after resolve deadline\n- [ ] Server pays rent on round creation, gets rent back on close\n- [ ] Pyth prices verifiable by anyone (oracle transparency)\n\n### FR-7: Game UI\n\nLive candlestick chart with betting panel, pool visualization, and countdown timer.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Large candlestick chart showing recent BTC/USD history\n- [ ] Current candle highlighted with live price indicator\n- [ ] Betting panel with amount input and GREEN/RED buttons\n- [ ] Pool sizes for GREEN and RED shown with distribution percentage\n- [ ] Active stake display if player has a pending bet\n- [ ] Countdown timer showing betting window remaining\n- [ ] Resolution animation: GREEN/RED result display\n- [ ] Clear indication of round outcome and player result\n\n---\n\n## On-Chain Architecture\n\n### Account PDAs\n\n| Account | Seeds | Purpose |\n|---------|-------|---------|\n| `CloseCallConfig` | `[\"closecall_config\"]` | Treasury, timing params, pause flag, max entries per side, Pyth feed address |\n| `CloseCallRound` | `[\"cc_round\", round_id]` | Per-round: entries (green/red), pool totals, open/close prices, outcome, phase |\n\nTwo PDA types. Same minimal pattern as coinflip.\n\n### Instructions\n\n| Instruction | Who calls | What it does |\n|-------------|-----------|-------------|\n| `initialize_config` | Authority | One-time config setup (treasury, timing, Pyth feed) |\n| `create_round` | Server | Creates round PDA, stores Pyth open price, pays rent |\n| `place_bet` | Player | Deposits SOL into round PDA, picks GREEN or RED |\n| `settle_round` | Server | Reads Pyth close price on-chain, determines outcome: pay winners or refund all |\n| `timeout_refund` | Anyone | Permissionless after resolve_deadline — refunds all players |\n| `force_close` | Authority | Emergency admin close — refunds all |\n\n6 instructions.\n\n### Fee Model\n\nFee = 3% of total pool, collected at settlement of decisive rounds.\n- Decisive round: `fee = 3% × total_pool`. Winners share `net_pool = total_pool - fee`.\n- Invalid round: NO fee. Full refund to all players.\n- Example: Green pool 7 SOL + Red pool 3 SOL = 10 SOL total. Green wins. Fee = 0.30 SOL. Green bettors share 9.70 SOL proportionally.\n\n### Shared Crate Reuse\n\nFrom `solana/shared/src/`:\n- `escrow.rs` — `transfer_lamports_from_pda`, `transfer_lamports_to_pda`, `close_pda`\n- `fees.rs` — `calculate_net_payout`, `split_fee`\n- `wager.rs` — `validate_wager`\n- `timeout.rs` — `is_expired`\n- `pause.rs` — `check_not_paused`\n\nProgram reads Pyth push oracle price accounts directly (no SDK dependency — manual parser in `pyth.rs`).\n\n---\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- A player can bet on candle direction, watch it resolve, and receive proportional auto-payout\n- Pari-mutuel payouts are mathematically correct for all pool distributions\n- Invalid rounds (equal price, one-sided, single player) refund fully with no fee\n- Settlement is idempotent and atomic\n- Price data is from a verifiable oracle source (Pyth Network)\n- Timeout refund protects players if backend fails\n\n---\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- Pyth Network price feed integration (on-chain `PriceUpdateV2` account)\n- Platform flexible betting system\n- On-chain settlement infrastructure (shared crate)\n- Real-time WebSocket for live price display (existing `packages/price-feeds`)\n\n## Assumptions\n\n- BTC/USD is the only asset at launch\n- Pyth Network provides sufficiently low-latency price data for 1-minute candles\n- 64 max entries per round fits within single-transaction compute budget for auto-payout\n- Backend clock worker reliably creates and settles rounds at minute boundaries\n\n---\n\n## Validation Plan\n\n| # | Acceptance Criterion | Validation Method | Evidence Required |\n|---|---------------------|-------------------|-------------------|\n| 1 | Round aligned to minute boundaries | Observe round transitions at :00 marks | Timestamps in logs |\n| 2 | Pari-mutuel payout correct | Multi-player round, verify proportional payouts | Calculation proof |\n| 3 | Equal price triggers full refund | Force equal-price condition | All bets returned, no fee |\n| 4 | One-sided pool triggers refund | All bets on one side | All bets returned, no fee |\n| 5 | Settlement idempotent | Attempt double-settle | Error response proof |\n| 6 | Price from Pyth verified | Compare on-chain price vs Pyth feed | Price comparison |\n| 7 | Timeout refund works | Let resolve deadline expire | Permissionless refund succeeds |\n| 8 | Auto-payout delivered | Win a round | Lamports arrive without claim tx |\n\n---\n\n## Completion Signal\n\n### Implementation Checklist\n\nItems are ordered by dependency. Each unchecked item = one autonomous iteration.\n\n#### On-chain program — DONE (iteration 0)\n- [x] [on-chain] CloseCallConfig + CloseCallRound PDAs, all 6 instructions, fee calc, invalid round handling, manual Pyth PriceUpdateV2 parser (`pyth.rs`)\n- [x] [test] Bankrun tests: 20 tests covering all instructions + edge cases (equal price, one-sided, single player, max entries, timeout)\n\n#### Phase 1: Pyth + Anchor Client\n- [x] [on-chain] Verify `pyth.rs` parser works with Pyth push oracle price accounts on devnet (BTC/USD feed). If the devnet Pyth accounts use a different format than PriceUpdateV2, adapt the parser. Find the correct Pyth BTC/USD price account address for devnet. Update bankrun tests with correct mock format if changed. Run `anchor build` + bankrun tests to confirm. (done: iteration 1)\n- [x] [engine] Copy `solana/target/idl/closecall.json` and `solana/target/types/closecall.ts` into `packages/anchor-client/src/`. Add `closecall` to the barrel export in `packages/anchor-client/src/index.ts` following the exact pattern used for coinflip and lordofrngs (IDL JSON import + type re-export). Add `CLOSECALL_PROGRAM_ID` constant to `packages/config/`. Run `pnpm lint` in the anchor-client package to confirm no errors. (done: iteration 2)\n\n#### Phase 2: Backend\n- [x] [backend] In `services/backend/src/worker/account-decoder.ts`, add `DecodedCloseCallRound` and `DecodedCloseCallConfig` interfaces + decoder functions using `BorshAccountsCoder` from the closecall IDL. Follow the exact pattern of the existing coinflip/lordofrngs decoders (bnToBigInt conversion, phase enum mapping). Export from module. Run `pnpm lint` to confirm. (done: iteration 3)\n- [x] [backend] In `services/backend/src/worker/settle-tx.ts`, add closecall settlement functions: `buildCreateRoundTx(roundId, pythPriceAccount)`, `buildSettleRoundTx(roundId, pythPriceAccount, winnerAccounts)`, `buildTimeoutRefundTx(roundId, playerAccounts)`. The backend reads the Pyth push oracle price account via `connection.getAccountInfo()` — no Hermes fetch needed. Follow the existing coinflip/lordofrngs settle pattern. Run `pnpm lint` to confirm. (done: iteration 4)\n- [x] [backend] Create `services/backend/src/worker/closecall-clock.ts` — a `CloseCallClockWorker` that runs on minute-boundary intervals. Each tick: (1) read Pyth BTC/USD push oracle price from Solana via RPC, (2) settle the previous round if it exists and candle has closed (call `buildSettleRoundTx`), (3) create a new round (call `buildCreateRoundTx` with open price from Pyth account). Use the existing `retry.ts` pattern for tx submission. Handle edge cases: no previous round, settlement failure (log + continue). Export worker class. (done: iteration 5)\n- [x] [backend] Extend DB: add `game = \"closecall\"` support to the `rounds` table (or create a new `closecall_rounds` table if schema differs significantly). Store: round_id, open_price, close_price, outcome, green_pool, red_pool, fee, created_at, settled_at, tx_signature. Add API routes: `GET /closecall/current-round` (returns active round + pool state), `GET /closecall/history` (last 20 settled rounds). Extend `GET /fairness/rounds/by-id/:roundId` to support closecall rounds. Follow the existing route creation pattern in `services/backend/src/routes/`. (done: iteration 6)\n- [x] [backend] Wire the `CloseCallClockWorker` into `services/backend/src/index.ts`: import, instantiate with config (Pyth BTC/USD account address, server keypair, connection, DB), start on backend boot. Add `PYTH_BTC_USD_ACCOUNT` env var to `.env` and config loading. Run `pnpm lint` across backend to confirm. Verify the backend starts without errors (even if clock worker won't find rounds on devnet yet). (done: iteration 7)\n\n#### Phase 3: Devnet Deploy\n- [x] [deploy] Deploy closecall program to devnet: `anchor deploy --provider.cluster devnet -p closecall`. Run `initialize_config` on devnet (treasury from `.env.devnet`, Pyth BTC/USD feed ID for devnet, 30s betting window, 32 max entries per side). Add `VITE_CLOSECALL_PROGRAM_ID=8TXq2XyHsk5AAMkoyk5QtG25xyyY7rTMHXrJRHRwjUpA` to `.env.devnet`. Verify by calling `create_round` + `place_bet` + `settle_round` manually against real Pyth prices. (done: iteration 8)\n\n#### Phase 4: Frontend Integration (existing mock scaffolding → real)\n\nNote: FE scaffolding already exists at `apps/platform/src/features/close-call/` with mock simulation. Route, sidebar nav entry, and component structure are already in place. These iterations swap mocks for real backend/on-chain integration.\n\n- [x] [frontend] Update `features/close-call/types.ts`: remove DOJI threshold, carryover, commit-reveal fields (`seedHash`, `serverSeed`, `blockHash`, `carryoverAmount`). Remove `claimPayout` from context actions (auto-payout). Fix constants: `BETTING_WINDOW_MS = 30000` (was 10000), `MIN_BET_AMOUNT` to 0.001 SOL, `MAX_BET_AMOUNT` to 100 SOL. Align `RoundPhase` with on-chain `CloseCallPhase` (Open/Settled/Refunded). Align `CandleOutcome` — remove \"doji\", add \"refund\". Update `PoolState` to match on-chain `green_pool`/`red_pool` fields. Run `pnpm lint` to confirm no type errors cascade. (done: iteration 30)\n- [x] [frontend] Rewrite `features/close-call/context/CloseCallContext.tsx`: replace `mock-simulation.ts` imports with real backend API calls (`GET /closecall/current-round` for active round + pools, `GET /closecall/history` for recent rounds). Poll current round every 2s (or use existing event subscription pattern from coinflip). Read Pyth BTC/USD price for chart via existing `packages/price-feeds` `usePriceSubscription(\"BTC\")`. Remove `claimPayout()`, remove carryover/jackpot state. Keep `placeBet()` as a stub that calls the wallet tx (wired in next iteration). Run `pnpm lint` + verify page loads without crash. (done: iteration 39)\n- [x] [frontend] Wire wallet integration for `place_bet`: in `CloseCallContext.tsx`, implement `placeBet()` to build and send a `place_bet` transaction using the closecall IDL from `packages/anchor-client`. Follow the exact pattern used in coinflip for tx building + signing via `useWallet()`. Handle errors: insufficient balance → toast, betting closed race → toast + refresh round, tx failure → toast with retry. On successful bet, optimistically update `userBet` in context, then confirm via next poll. Remove `mock-simulation.ts` and `payout-calculator.ts` if fully replaced. Run `pnpm lint`. (done: iteration 40)\n- [x] [frontend] Add `/close-call/:roundId` deep-link page: create `pages/CloseCallRoundPage.tsx` (follow pattern of `CoinflipRoundPage`). Fetch round data from `GET /fairness/rounds/by-id/:roundId`. Display: open price, close price, outcome (Green/Red/Refund), green pool, red pool, total pool, fee collected, entries list, settlement tx signature. Add route to `App.tsx`. Link from round history list. Run `pnpm lint`. (done: iteration 41)\n\n#### Phase 5: Testing\n- [x] [test] Update visual baselines for close-call pages. Run `pnpm test:visual` to identify failures, then `pnpm test:visual:update` to regenerate. **Before committing**: read old baseline and new screenshot for each changed page (use Read tool on PNG files). Evaluate: **PASS** (changes clearly match spec intent) → commit. **REVIEW** (unexpected areas changed) → save diff images, describe in history.md, output blocker. **FAIL** (broken layout) → fix code, don't update baselines. (done: iteration 42)\n- [x] [test] ~~Add local deterministic E2E coverage~~ N/A: Close Call requires Pyth oracle price accounts (PriceUpdateV2 owned by Pyth Solana Receiver) on localnet — no Pyth program stack deployed locally. Backend clock worker also needs Pyth to create rounds. Frontend has no mock mode fallback. Devnet E2E (next item) provides integration coverage with real Pyth data. (done: iteration 43)\n- [x] [test] Add visual route/state coverage in `e2e/visual/**`; run `pnpm test:visual` and update baselines only for intentional UI changes (done: iteration 44)\n- [x] [test] If external provider/oracle/VRF integration is in scope, add devnet real-provider E2E coverage in `e2e/devnet/**` with env validation + retry/backoff (or mark N/A with reason) (done: iteration 45)\n\n### Testing Requirements\n\nThe agent MUST complete ALL before outputting the completion signal:\n\n#### Code Quality\n- [ ] All existing tests pass\n- [x] New bankrun tests for all 6 instructions (done: iteration 0)\n- [x] New tests for pari-mutuel payout calculations (done: iteration 0)\n- [x] New tests for invalid round conditions (done: iteration 0)\n- [ ] No lint errors\n\n#### Functional Verification\n- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified\n- [ ] Edge cases: equal price, single-sided pool, max entries reached, timeout refund\n- [ ] Settlement idempotency verified\n- [ ] Auto-payout delivers correct amounts\n\n#### Visual Verification\n- [ ] Chart and betting UI correct on desktop\n- [ ] Mobile responsive layout works\n\n#### Console/Network Check\n- [ ] No JS console errors\n- [ ] No failed network requests\n\n### Iteration Instructions\n\nIf ANY check fails:\n1. Identify the specific issue\n2. Fix the code\n3. Re-run tests\n4. Re-verify all criteria\n5. Check again\n\n**Only when ALL checks pass, output:** `<promise>DONE</promise>`\n","numLines":316,"startLine":1,"totalLines":316}}}
