{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WYu54mwN4DZbSvnGepJrDS","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# RNG Utopia - Scope\n     2→\n     3→Non-custodial P2P gaming platform on Solana, scoped for practical V1 execution.\n     4→\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## 1) Scope Goal\n     8→\n     9→Deliver a launchable V1 focused on:\n    10→- Two core games\n    11→- On-chain settlement\n    12→- Verifiable fairness\n    13→- Basic player history/profile\n    14→\n    15→This document defines what is in scope, out of scope, and deferred. It intentionally avoids implementation-level details.\n    16→\n    17→---\n    18→\n    19→## 2) Product Scope\n    20→\n    21→### In Scope (V1 Launch)\n    22→- Lord of the RNGs\n    23→- Coinflip\n    24→- Wallet connection (normal Solana wallet flow first)\n    25→- Non-custodial transaction flow for all financial actions\n    26→- Fairness verification experience for each game\n    27→- Basic user profile and history views\n    28→- Basic operational controls (pause/resume, monitoring, incident response)\n    29→\n    30→### Out of Scope (V1 Launch)\n    31→- Internal custodial balance model\n    32→- Multi-chain support\n    33→- Token launch and token utility\n    34→- Referrals/rakeback programs\n    35→- Lootboxes\n    36→- Profile customization/social linking\n    37→\n    38→### Deferred to V1.5 / V2\n    39→- Global chat\n    40→- Chat rewards\n    41→- Boss raids\n    42→- Deep quests system\n    43→- Advanced gamification loops\n    44→- Expanded social features\n    45→\n    46→---\n    47→\n    48→## 3) Architecture Direction (Locked)\n    49→\n    50→### Core Decisions\n    51→- Chain: Solana\n    52→- Custody: Non-custodial\n    53→- Program model: Standard Anchor programs (per-game + shared crate, see `docs/specs/004-shared-infrastructure/spec.md`)\n    54→- Wallet rollout: normal wallets first, embedded wallet expansion later\n    55→\n    56→### Explicit Constraint\n    57→- Do not build a temporary minimal program with planned rewrite.\n    58→- Continue on a single architecture path: program-per-game + shared Rust crate (`solana/shared/`). See pivot doc (`docs/pivot-doc.md`).\n    59→\n    60→---\n    61→\n    62→## 4) Source of Truth and Boundaries\n    63→\n    64→### On-Chain Source of Truth\n    65→- All money movement\n    66→- Round settlement outcomes\n    67→- Payout eligibility and claim state\n    68→\n    69→### Off-Chain Responsibilities\n    70→- Read models and indexing for UX/performance\n    71→- Basic profile/history aggregation\n    72→- Backend-assisted fairness services (secret generation, partial-sign create flows, settlement workers, verification endpoints)\n    73→- Fairness presentation and verification UX\n    74→- Real-time coordination where needed for UX\n    75→\n    76→### Rule\n    77→- If it changes user funds or determines payouts, it must be validated on-chain.\n    78→\n    79→---\n    80→\n    81→## 5) V1 Game Scope\n    82→\n    83→### Lord of the RNGs (V1)\n    84→- Multiplayer tier participation with multiple entries per player\n    85→- Backend-assisted hybrid fairness (commitment at create, public entropy capture at spin/start, automatic settlement)\n    86→- Round settlement with timeout-protected refund fallback\n    87→- Fairness verification path backed by public verification payloads and on-chain settlement evidence\n    88→\n    89→### Coinflip (V1)\n    90→- Match creation/join flow\n    91→- Backend-partially-signed create flow with wallet-authenticated requests\n    92→- Hybrid fairness outcome derived from revealed secret + future slot-hash entropy\n    93→- Automatic settlement with timeout-protected refund fallback\n    94→- Fairness verification path backed by public verification payloads and on-chain settlement evidence\n    95→\n    96→### Shared Game Requirements\n    97→- Idempotent action handling\n    98→- Replay protection for signed actions\n    99→- Clear error states for failed transactions\n   100→- Devnet-first validation before any production rollout\n   101→\n   102→---\n   103→\n   104→## 6) Functional Requirements (V1)\n   105→\n   106→- Users can connect wallets and perform game actions\n   107→- All financial interactions are on-chain\n   108→- Coinflip and Lord of the RNGs are playable end-to-end\n   109→- Users can verify fairness for completed rounds/matches\n   110→- Users can view basic profile and recent history\n   111→- Operators can pause/resume games\n   112→\n   113→---\n   114→\n   115→## 7) Non-Functional Requirements (V1)\n   116→\n   117→- Reliability: stable under expected early load\n   118→- Observability: errors and key events are visible\n   119→- Security baseline: rate limiting, validation, abuse protections\n   120→- UX baseline: clear transaction state feedback and recovery paths\n   121→- Operational readiness: incident checklist and rollback procedure\n   122→\n   123→---\n   124→\n   125→## 8) Delivery Plan\n   126→\n   127→### Phase 0 - Alignment and Readiness\n   128→- Confirm architecture decisions and provider selections\n   129→- Confirm game-level acceptance criteria\n   130→- Finalize launch scope freeze\n   131→\n   132→### Phase 1 - Coinflip End-to-End\n   133→- Complete real Coinflip game loop with backend-assisted create, automatic settlement, and on-chain payout verification\n   134→- Deliver fairness verification view for Coinflip\n   135→- Validate on devnet with end-to-end flows\n   136→\n   137→### Phase 2 - Lord of the RNGs End-to-End\n   138→- Complete real Lord of the RNGs game loop with backend-assisted fairness and on-chain payout verification\n   139→- Deliver fairness verification view for Lord of the RNGs\n   140→- Validate on devnet with end-to-end flows\n   141→\n   142→### Phase 3 - Profile/History + Ops Hardening\n   143→- Basic player profile/history from indexed data\n   144→- Operational controls, alerting, and runbook\n   145→- Stability pass and launch readiness checks\n   146→\n   147→### Phase 4 - Launch Gate\n   148→- Devnet validation complete\n   149→- Scope lock maintained\n   150→- No critical blockers remaining\n   151→\n   152→---\n   153→\n   154→## 9) Launch Readiness Checklist (V1)\n   155→\n   156→### Functional\n   157→- [ ] Wallet connection works for launch wallet path\n   158→- [ ] Lord of the RNGs playable end-to-end with real settlement path\n   159→- [ ] Coinflip playable end-to-end with real settlement path\n   160→- [ ] Fairness verification works for Lord of the RNGs\n   161→- [ ] Fairness verification works for Coinflip\n   162→- [ ] Basic profile/history available and accurate\n   163→\n   164→### Security and Integrity\n   165→- [ ] On-chain payout invariants validated\n   166→- [ ] Idempotency and replay protections validated\n   167→- [ ] Critical abuse paths mitigated\n   168→- [ ] Emergency pause tested\n   169→\n   170→### Operational\n   171→- [ ] Monitoring and error reporting active\n   172→- [ ] Incident and rollback playbook documented\n   173→- [ ] Devnet soak tests completed\n   174→\n   175→---\n   176→\n   177→## 10) Risks and Mitigations\n   178→\n   179→### Risk: Scope Expansion\n   180→- Mitigation: strict V1 boundary; defer social/gamification features\n   181→\n   182→### Risk: Multiplayer Jackpot Fairness Complexity\n   183→- Mitigation: isolate acceptance criteria for entry weighting, winner selection, backend settlement, and public verification early\n   184→\n   185→### Risk: First-Game Delivery Risk\n   186→- Mitigation: use Coinflip as first implementation target, then add Lord of the RNGs after core settlement and fairness flows are proven\n   187→\n   188→### Risk: Integration Drift from Existing Repo\n   189→- Mitigation: keep standard Anchor path (per-game + shared crate), avoid parallel architecture tracks\n   190→\n   191→### Risk: Wallet UX Friction\n   192→- Mitigation: ship stable normal wallet flow first; evaluate embedded wallet in V1.5\n   193→\n   194→---\n   195→\n   196→## 11) Success Metrics (V1)\n   197→\n   198→Primary:\n   199→- Successful completion rate of game rounds/matches\n   200→- Settlement correctness and claim success rate\n   201→- Fairness verification usage and pass rate\n   202→- Critical error rate within acceptable threshold\n   203→\n   204→Secondary:\n   205→- Early retention and repeat play behavior\n   206→- Time-to-complete for core game loop\n   207→\n   208→---\n   209→\n   210→## 12) Post-Launch Expansion\n   211→\n   212→### V1.5\n   213→- Chat (no rewards)\n   214→- Intro quests\n   215→- Simple points layer\n   216→- Embedded wallet rollout option\n   217→\n   218→### V2\n   219→- Chat rewards\n   220→- Boss raids\n   221→- Advanced quests and gamification depth\n   222→- Additional game(s)\n   223→- Referral system and broader social loops\n   224→\n   225→---\n   226→\n   227→## 13) Scope Governance\n   228→\n   229→- Any feature not listed under V1 In Scope is excluded by default.\n   230→- Deferred features require explicit re-prioritization after launch readiness review.\n   231→- Changes to custody model or architecture path require a separate decision memo.\n   232→\n   233→---\n   234→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"efe120e9-7ceb-4e75-b227-230da807bdef","uuid":"6cfb5f05-798b-4331-b454-f14a9c7af8fe","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/docs/SCOPE.md","content":"# RNG Utopia - Scope\n\nNon-custodial P2P gaming platform on Solana, scoped for practical V1 execution.\n\n---\n\n## 1) Scope Goal\n\nDeliver a launchable V1 focused on:\n- Two core games\n- On-chain settlement\n- Verifiable fairness\n- Basic player history/profile\n\nThis document defines what is in scope, out of scope, and deferred. It intentionally avoids implementation-level details.\n\n---\n\n## 2) Product Scope\n\n### In Scope (V1 Launch)\n- Lord of the RNGs\n- Coinflip\n- Wallet connection (normal Solana wallet flow first)\n- Non-custodial transaction flow for all financial actions\n- Fairness verification experience for each game\n- Basic user profile and history views\n- Basic operational controls (pause/resume, monitoring, incident response)\n\n### Out of Scope (V1 Launch)\n- Internal custodial balance model\n- Multi-chain support\n- Token launch and token utility\n- Referrals/rakeback programs\n- Lootboxes\n- Profile customization/social linking\n\n### Deferred to V1.5 / V2\n- Global chat\n- Chat rewards\n- Boss raids\n- Deep quests system\n- Advanced gamification loops\n- Expanded social features\n\n---\n\n## 3) Architecture Direction (Locked)\n\n### Core Decisions\n- Chain: Solana\n- Custody: Non-custodial\n- Program model: Standard Anchor programs (per-game + shared crate, see `docs/specs/004-shared-infrastructure/spec.md`)\n- Wallet rollout: normal wallets first, embedded wallet expansion later\n\n### Explicit Constraint\n- Do not build a temporary minimal program with planned rewrite.\n- Continue on a single architecture path: program-per-game + shared Rust crate (`solana/shared/`). See pivot doc (`docs/pivot-doc.md`).\n\n---\n\n## 4) Source of Truth and Boundaries\n\n### On-Chain Source of Truth\n- All money movement\n- Round settlement outcomes\n- Payout eligibility and claim state\n\n### Off-Chain Responsibilities\n- Read models and indexing for UX/performance\n- Basic profile/history aggregation\n- Backend-assisted fairness services (secret generation, partial-sign create flows, settlement workers, verification endpoints)\n- Fairness presentation and verification UX\n- Real-time coordination where needed for UX\n\n### Rule\n- If it changes user funds or determines payouts, it must be validated on-chain.\n\n---\n\n## 5) V1 Game Scope\n\n### Lord of the RNGs (V1)\n- Multiplayer tier participation with multiple entries per player\n- Backend-assisted hybrid fairness (commitment at create, public entropy capture at spin/start, automatic settlement)\n- Round settlement with timeout-protected refund fallback\n- Fairness verification path backed by public verification payloads and on-chain settlement evidence\n\n### Coinflip (V1)\n- Match creation/join flow\n- Backend-partially-signed create flow with wallet-authenticated requests\n- Hybrid fairness outcome derived from revealed secret + future slot-hash entropy\n- Automatic settlement with timeout-protected refund fallback\n- Fairness verification path backed by public verification payloads and on-chain settlement evidence\n\n### Shared Game Requirements\n- Idempotent action handling\n- Replay protection for signed actions\n- Clear error states for failed transactions\n- Devnet-first validation before any production rollout\n\n---\n\n## 6) Functional Requirements (V1)\n\n- Users can connect wallets and perform game actions\n- All financial interactions are on-chain\n- Coinflip and Lord of the RNGs are playable end-to-end\n- Users can verify fairness for completed rounds/matches\n- Users can view basic profile and recent history\n- Operators can pause/resume games\n\n---\n\n## 7) Non-Functional Requirements (V1)\n\n- Reliability: stable under expected early load\n- Observability: errors and key events are visible\n- Security baseline: rate limiting, validation, abuse protections\n- UX baseline: clear transaction state feedback and recovery paths\n- Operational readiness: incident checklist and rollback procedure\n\n---\n\n## 8) Delivery Plan\n\n### Phase 0 - Alignment and Readiness\n- Confirm architecture decisions and provider selections\n- Confirm game-level acceptance criteria\n- Finalize launch scope freeze\n\n### Phase 1 - Coinflip End-to-End\n- Complete real Coinflip game loop with backend-assisted create, automatic settlement, and on-chain payout verification\n- Deliver fairness verification view for Coinflip\n- Validate on devnet with end-to-end flows\n\n### Phase 2 - Lord of the RNGs End-to-End\n- Complete real Lord of the RNGs game loop with backend-assisted fairness and on-chain payout verification\n- Deliver fairness verification view for Lord of the RNGs\n- Validate on devnet with end-to-end flows\n\n### Phase 3 - Profile/History + Ops Hardening\n- Basic player profile/history from indexed data\n- Operational controls, alerting, and runbook\n- Stability pass and launch readiness checks\n\n### Phase 4 - Launch Gate\n- Devnet validation complete\n- Scope lock maintained\n- No critical blockers remaining\n\n---\n\n## 9) Launch Readiness Checklist (V1)\n\n### Functional\n- [ ] Wallet connection works for launch wallet path\n- [ ] Lord of the RNGs playable end-to-end with real settlement path\n- [ ] Coinflip playable end-to-end with real settlement path\n- [ ] Fairness verification works for Lord of the RNGs\n- [ ] Fairness verification works for Coinflip\n- [ ] Basic profile/history available and accurate\n\n### Security and Integrity\n- [ ] On-chain payout invariants validated\n- [ ] Idempotency and replay protections validated\n- [ ] Critical abuse paths mitigated\n- [ ] Emergency pause tested\n\n### Operational\n- [ ] Monitoring and error reporting active\n- [ ] Incident and rollback playbook documented\n- [ ] Devnet soak tests completed\n\n---\n\n## 10) Risks and Mitigations\n\n### Risk: Scope Expansion\n- Mitigation: strict V1 boundary; defer social/gamification features\n\n### Risk: Multiplayer Jackpot Fairness Complexity\n- Mitigation: isolate acceptance criteria for entry weighting, winner selection, backend settlement, and public verification early\n\n### Risk: First-Game Delivery Risk\n- Mitigation: use Coinflip as first implementation target, then add Lord of the RNGs after core settlement and fairness flows are proven\n\n### Risk: Integration Drift from Existing Repo\n- Mitigation: keep standard Anchor path (per-game + shared crate), avoid parallel architecture tracks\n\n### Risk: Wallet UX Friction\n- Mitigation: ship stable normal wallet flow first; evaluate embedded wallet in V1.5\n\n---\n\n## 11) Success Metrics (V1)\n\nPrimary:\n- Successful completion rate of game rounds/matches\n- Settlement correctness and claim success rate\n- Fairness verification usage and pass rate\n- Critical error rate within acceptable threshold\n\nSecondary:\n- Early retention and repeat play behavior\n- Time-to-complete for core game loop\n\n---\n\n## 12) Post-Launch Expansion\n\n### V1.5\n- Chat (no rewards)\n- Intro quests\n- Simple points layer\n- Embedded wallet rollout option\n\n### V2\n- Chat rewards\n- Boss raids\n- Advanced quests and gamification depth\n- Additional game(s)\n- Referral system and broader social loops\n\n---\n\n## 13) Scope Governance\n\n- Any feature not listed under V1 In Scope is excluded by default.\n- Deferred features require explicit re-prioritization after launch readiness review.\n- Changes to custody model or architecture path require a separate decision memo.\n\n---\n","numLines":234,"startLine":1,"totalLines":234}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017mtqV4QYkX9SbYpyp5Tuo8","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Decision Log\n     2→\n     3→Track key architectural and product decisions as they're made.\n     4→\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## 2026-02-09 - Initial Setup\n     8→\n     9→### Decision: Coinflip First, Lord of the RNGs Second\n    10→**Date**: 2026-02-09\n    11→**Decision**: Phase 1 will be Coinflip, Phase 2 will be Lord of the RNGs\n    12→**Rationale**: Coinflip and Lord of the RNGs share a backend-assisted, non-real-time settlement shape, letting us validate core fairness and settlement flows before tackling Crash timing complexity.\n    13→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    14→\n    15→### Decision: Standard Anchor Programs (Not BOLT ECS)\n    16→**Date**: 2026-02-17 (revised from 2026-02-09)\n    17→**Decision**: Use standard Anchor `#[program]` / `#[derive(Accounts)]` architecture. Legacy BOLT ECS code removed.\n    18→**Rationale**: BOLT ECS adds unnecessary abstraction for our use case (simple 1v1 games). Standard Anchor is well-documented, widely supported by tooling (bankrun, IDL gen), and simpler to debug. Separate programs per game (coinflip, platform) + shared lib crate for constants.\n    19→**Alternatives considered**: BOLT ECS (original choice, too complex for V1), single monolith program (poor separation of concerns).\n    20→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    21→\n    22→### Decision: Normal Wallets First, Privy Later\n    23→**Date**: 2026-02-09\n    24→**Decision**: Ship normal Solana wallet flow first (Phantom/Solflare), add Privy embedded wallets in V1.5\n    25→**Rationale**: Normal wallets are simpler to validate. Privy adds complexity (session keys, embedded wallet creation) that can be added after core game loop is proven.\n    26→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    27→\n    28→### Decision: Two-Repo Structure\n    29→**Date**: 2026-02-09\n    30→**Decision**: Root repo for project management/docs, `sources/rng-utopia/` as git submodule pointing to code repo\n    31→**Rationale**: Clean separation of project context vs codebase. Allows independent versioning.\n    32→**Status**: ✅ Implemented\n    33→\n    34→### Decision: FE Entrypoint Is apps/platform\n    35→**Date**: 2026-02-11\n    36→**Decision**: Treat `sources/rng-utopia/apps/platform/` as the authoritative frontend runtime entrypoint.\n    37→**Rationale**: This is the currently deployed shell containing active feature mocks; other app folders are scaffolds and not required for FE runtime verification.\n    38→**Alternatives considered**: Building all app scaffolds as hard requirement (`build:all`).\n    39→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    40→\n    41→### Decision: Non-Platform Apps Are Platform-Only Scaffolds\n    42→**Date**: 2026-02-11\n    43→**Decision**: Keep non-platform app folders under `sources/rng-utopia/apps/` as platform-only scaffolds, not standalone deployment targets.\n    44→**Rationale**: Runtime game flows are embedded in `apps/platform` and this preserves structure without forcing standalone Vite app parity for each scaffold.\n    45→**Alternatives considered**: Making each app independently buildable and deployable in the current phase.\n    46→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    47→\n    48→---\n    49→\n    50→## 2026-02-25 - Architecture Pivot\n    51→\n    52→### Decision: Solana Settlement & Fairness Standard (Pivot Doc)\n    53→**Date**: 2026-02-25\n    54→**Decision**: Program-per-game + shared Rust crate (`solana/shared/`), standardized lifecycle with timeout/pause/fee/refund invariants across all 8 games.\n    55→**Rationale**: Consistency across all games, single audit path, compile-time guarantees via shared crate. No shared on-chain kernel — consistency from compilation, not CPI. See `docs/pivot-doc.md` for full architecture.\n    56→**Alternatives considered**: Shared on-chain EscrowKernel program (CPI overhead, larger blast radius), per-game bespoke state machines (inconsistent, harder to audit).\n    57→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    58→\n    59→### Decision: VRF Provider = Orao (MagicBlock dropped)\n    60→**Date**: 2026-02-25\n    61→**Decision**: Replace MagicBlock Ephemeral VRF with **Orao** as the single VRF provider for V1.\n    62→**Rationale**: Orao proved straightforward devnet integration and fast fulfillment in live smoke tests. This gives us one VRF integration path for Coinflip and Lord of RNGs while preserving the pivot architecture.\n    63→**Alternatives considered**: Switchboard (reachable on devnet but required additional callback-consumer wiring for equivalent end-to-end benchmarking), keeping MagicBlock VRF (limited VRF focus, uncertain long-term support).\n    64→**Status**: ❌ Reversed\n    65→\n    66→### Decision: Crash Fairness Model — VRF + Commit-Reveal (Not HMAC-Only)\n    67→**Date**: 2026-02-25\n    68→**Decision**: Crash uses VRF seed (requested pre-round) + commit-reveal for server result verification. Replaces the HMAC seed chain model.\n    69→**Rationale**: VRF provides unpredictable seed generation without pre-commitment chains. Commit-reveal proves server honesty for the off-chain engine. Same two fairness primitives used across all games — no per-game mechanisms.\n    70→**Alternatives considered**: HMAC seed chain (Bustabit model — works but requires separate pre-commitment infrastructure not shared with other games).\n    71→**Status**: ❌ Reversed\n    72→\n    73→---\n    74→\n    75→## 2026-03-11 - Fairness Realignment\n    76→\n    77→### Decision: V1 Fairness Standard = Backend-Assisted Hybrid Fairness\n    78→**Date**: 2026-03-11\n    79→**Decision**: V1 fairness defaults to backend-assisted commit-reveal with future slot-hash entropy, wallet-authenticated create requests, backend-partially-signed create transactions, backend-submitted settlement, and permissionless timeout refunds as the liveness guarantee.\n    80→**Rationale**: This aligns product, on-chain, backend, and E2E flows under one default model. It removes the mismatch between frontend docs, backend docs, and newer fairness specs, while preserving public verification and strong timeout guarantees.\n    81→**Alternatives considered**: Keeping VRF as the default V1 path (too expensive and inconsistent with the current backend contract), pure client-side secret generation (weaker trust model), HMAC-only server fairness (insufficient on-chain verifiability).\n    82→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    83→\n    84→### Decision: VRF Is Deferred / Optional, Not Default V1 Infrastructure\n    85→**Date**: 2026-03-11\n    86→**Decision**: VRF is no longer the default fairness path for V1 game specs. If a future game truly requires VRF, it must be documented explicitly as an exception or deferred feature rather than assumed platform-wide.\n    87→**Rationale**: The current target architecture is the hybrid fairness model captured in specs `005-hybrid-fairness` and `006-fairness-backend`. Leaving VRF marked as default causes spec drift and incorrect test planning.\n    88→**Alternatives considered**: Keeping Orao as the universal default, or removing all mention of VRF entirely.\n    89→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    90→\n    91→---\n    92→\n    93→## 2026-03-12 - Match ID and Profile Removal\n    94→\n    95→### Decision: Remove PlayerProfile, Use Backend-Generated Random Match IDs\n    96→**Date**: 2026-03-12\n    97→**Decision**: Replace nonce-based PDA derivation (`[\"match\", creator, nonce.to_le_bytes()]`) with backend-generated random 8-byte match IDs (`[\"match\", creator, match_id]`). Remove `PlayerProfile` entirely — stats move off-chain. Allow multiple concurrent matches per user.\n    98→**Rationale**: The `PlayerProfile.match_nonce` pattern required a 3-instruction atomic transaction (create_player_profile + increment_match_nonce + create_match), added UX friction (rent for profile PDA), prevented concurrent matches per user, and required CPI from game programs into the platform program during settlement. Random match IDs eliminate all of these issues while keeping PDA derivation deterministic and collision-free (8 random bytes = 2^64 possible IDs).\n    99→**Impact**: On-chain: coinflip `nonce: u64` → `match_id: [u8; 8]`, settle instruction drops 3 accounts (creatorProfile, opponentProfile, platformProgram). Platform program loses 3 instructions (create_player_profile, increment_match_nonce, update_player_profile) and the PlayerProfile state. Lord of RNGs claim_payout drops profile CPI. Shared crate `cpi.rs` deleted. Backend: `nonce` removed from request body, auth canonical JSON, and DB schema; replaced with server-generated `match_id`. Frontend: nonce fetching and profile checks removed from create flow.\n   100→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n   101→\n   102→---\n   103→\n   104→## Template for New Decisions\n   105→\n   106→```markdown\n   107→### Decision: [Title]\n   108→**Date**: YYYY-MM-DD\n   109→**Decision**: [What was decided]\n   110→**Rationale**: [Why this choice]\n   111→**Alternatives considered**: [Other options]\n   112→**Status**: [✅ Locked / 🟡 Revisitable / ❌ Reversed]\n   113→```\n   114→\n   115→---\n   116→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"efe120e9-7ceb-4e75-b227-230da807bdef","uuid":"04de9e18-851d-409c-8da0-a01f9ca90079","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/docs/DECISIONS.md","content":"# Decision Log\n\nTrack key architectural and product decisions as they're made.\n\n---\n\n## 2026-02-09 - Initial Setup\n\n### Decision: Coinflip First, Lord of the RNGs Second\n**Date**: 2026-02-09\n**Decision**: Phase 1 will be Coinflip, Phase 2 will be Lord of the RNGs\n**Rationale**: Coinflip and Lord of the RNGs share a backend-assisted, non-real-time settlement shape, letting us validate core fairness and settlement flows before tackling Crash timing complexity.\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: Standard Anchor Programs (Not BOLT ECS)\n**Date**: 2026-02-17 (revised from 2026-02-09)\n**Decision**: Use standard Anchor `#[program]` / `#[derive(Accounts)]` architecture. Legacy BOLT ECS code removed.\n**Rationale**: BOLT ECS adds unnecessary abstraction for our use case (simple 1v1 games). Standard Anchor is well-documented, widely supported by tooling (bankrun, IDL gen), and simpler to debug. Separate programs per game (coinflip, platform) + shared lib crate for constants.\n**Alternatives considered**: BOLT ECS (original choice, too complex for V1), single monolith program (poor separation of concerns).\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: Normal Wallets First, Privy Later\n**Date**: 2026-02-09\n**Decision**: Ship normal Solana wallet flow first (Phantom/Solflare), add Privy embedded wallets in V1.5\n**Rationale**: Normal wallets are simpler to validate. Privy adds complexity (session keys, embedded wallet creation) that can be added after core game loop is proven.\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: Two-Repo Structure\n**Date**: 2026-02-09\n**Decision**: Root repo for project management/docs, `sources/rng-utopia/` as git submodule pointing to code repo\n**Rationale**: Clean separation of project context vs codebase. Allows independent versioning.\n**Status**: ✅ Implemented\n\n### Decision: FE Entrypoint Is apps/platform\n**Date**: 2026-02-11\n**Decision**: Treat `sources/rng-utopia/apps/platform/` as the authoritative frontend runtime entrypoint.\n**Rationale**: This is the currently deployed shell containing active feature mocks; other app folders are scaffolds and not required for FE runtime verification.\n**Alternatives considered**: Building all app scaffolds as hard requirement (`build:all`).\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: Non-Platform Apps Are Platform-Only Scaffolds\n**Date**: 2026-02-11\n**Decision**: Keep non-platform app folders under `sources/rng-utopia/apps/` as platform-only scaffolds, not standalone deployment targets.\n**Rationale**: Runtime game flows are embedded in `apps/platform` and this preserves structure without forcing standalone Vite app parity for each scaffold.\n**Alternatives considered**: Making each app independently buildable and deployable in the current phase.\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n---\n\n## 2026-02-25 - Architecture Pivot\n\n### Decision: Solana Settlement & Fairness Standard (Pivot Doc)\n**Date**: 2026-02-25\n**Decision**: Program-per-game + shared Rust crate (`solana/shared/`), standardized lifecycle with timeout/pause/fee/refund invariants across all 8 games.\n**Rationale**: Consistency across all games, single audit path, compile-time guarantees via shared crate. No shared on-chain kernel — consistency from compilation, not CPI. See `docs/pivot-doc.md` for full architecture.\n**Alternatives considered**: Shared on-chain EscrowKernel program (CPI overhead, larger blast radius), per-game bespoke state machines (inconsistent, harder to audit).\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: VRF Provider = Orao (MagicBlock dropped)\n**Date**: 2026-02-25\n**Decision**: Replace MagicBlock Ephemeral VRF with **Orao** as the single VRF provider for V1.\n**Rationale**: Orao proved straightforward devnet integration and fast fulfillment in live smoke tests. This gives us one VRF integration path for Coinflip and Lord of RNGs while preserving the pivot architecture.\n**Alternatives considered**: Switchboard (reachable on devnet but required additional callback-consumer wiring for equivalent end-to-end benchmarking), keeping MagicBlock VRF (limited VRF focus, uncertain long-term support).\n**Status**: ❌ Reversed\n\n### Decision: Crash Fairness Model — VRF + Commit-Reveal (Not HMAC-Only)\n**Date**: 2026-02-25\n**Decision**: Crash uses VRF seed (requested pre-round) + commit-reveal for server result verification. Replaces the HMAC seed chain model.\n**Rationale**: VRF provides unpredictable seed generation without pre-commitment chains. Commit-reveal proves server honesty for the off-chain engine. Same two fairness primitives used across all games — no per-game mechanisms.\n**Alternatives considered**: HMAC seed chain (Bustabit model — works but requires separate pre-commitment infrastructure not shared with other games).\n**Status**: ❌ Reversed\n\n---\n\n## 2026-03-11 - Fairness Realignment\n\n### Decision: V1 Fairness Standard = Backend-Assisted Hybrid Fairness\n**Date**: 2026-03-11\n**Decision**: V1 fairness defaults to backend-assisted commit-reveal with future slot-hash entropy, wallet-authenticated create requests, backend-partially-signed create transactions, backend-submitted settlement, and permissionless timeout refunds as the liveness guarantee.\n**Rationale**: This aligns product, on-chain, backend, and E2E flows under one default model. It removes the mismatch between frontend docs, backend docs, and newer fairness specs, while preserving public verification and strong timeout guarantees.\n**Alternatives considered**: Keeping VRF as the default V1 path (too expensive and inconsistent with the current backend contract), pure client-side secret generation (weaker trust model), HMAC-only server fairness (insufficient on-chain verifiability).\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: VRF Is Deferred / Optional, Not Default V1 Infrastructure\n**Date**: 2026-03-11\n**Decision**: VRF is no longer the default fairness path for V1 game specs. If a future game truly requires VRF, it must be documented explicitly as an exception or deferred feature rather than assumed platform-wide.\n**Rationale**: The current target architecture is the hybrid fairness model captured in specs `005-hybrid-fairness` and `006-fairness-backend`. Leaving VRF marked as default causes spec drift and incorrect test planning.\n**Alternatives considered**: Keeping Orao as the universal default, or removing all mention of VRF entirely.\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n---\n\n## 2026-03-12 - Match ID and Profile Removal\n\n### Decision: Remove PlayerProfile, Use Backend-Generated Random Match IDs\n**Date**: 2026-03-12\n**Decision**: Replace nonce-based PDA derivation (`[\"match\", creator, nonce.to_le_bytes()]`) with backend-generated random 8-byte match IDs (`[\"match\", creator, match_id]`). Remove `PlayerProfile` entirely — stats move off-chain. Allow multiple concurrent matches per user.\n**Rationale**: The `PlayerProfile.match_nonce` pattern required a 3-instruction atomic transaction (create_player_profile + increment_match_nonce + create_match), added UX friction (rent for profile PDA), prevented concurrent matches per user, and required CPI from game programs into the platform program during settlement. Random match IDs eliminate all of these issues while keeping PDA derivation deterministic and collision-free (8 random bytes = 2^64 possible IDs).\n**Impact**: On-chain: coinflip `nonce: u64` → `match_id: [u8; 8]`, settle instruction drops 3 accounts (creatorProfile, opponentProfile, platformProgram). Platform program loses 3 instructions (create_player_profile, increment_match_nonce, update_player_profile) and the PlayerProfile state. Lord of RNGs claim_payout drops profile CPI. Shared crate `cpi.rs` deleted. Backend: `nonce` removed from request body, auth canonical JSON, and DB schema; replaced with server-generated `match_id`. Frontend: nonce fetching and profile checks removed from create flow.\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n---\n\n## Template for New Decisions\n\n```markdown\n### Decision: [Title]\n**Date**: YYYY-MM-DD\n**Decision**: [What was decided]\n**Rationale**: [Why this choice]\n**Alternatives considered**: [Other options]\n**Status**: [✅ Locked / 🟡 Revisitable / ❌ Reversed]\n```\n\n---\n","numLines":116,"startLine":1,"totalLines":116}}}
